==Absolute convergence of integrals==

The integral formula_163 of a real or complex-valued function is said to converge absolutely if formula_164 One also says that formula_124 is absolutely integrable. The issue of absolute integrability is intricate and depends on whether the Riemann, Lebesgue, or Kurzweil-Henstock (gauge) integral is considered; for the Riemann integral, it also depends on whether we only consider integrability in its proper sense (formula_124 and formula_48 both bounded), or permit the more general case of improper integrals.

As a standard property of the Riemann integral, when formula_168 is a bounded interval, every continuous function is bounded and (Riemann) integrable, and since formula_124 continuous implies formula_170 continuous, every continuous function is absolutely integrable. In fact, since formula_171 is Riemann integrable on formula_172 if formula_124 is (properly) integrable and formula_174 is continuous, it follows that formula_175 is properly Riemann integrable if formula_124 is. However, this implication does not hold in the case of improper integrals. For instance, the function formula_177 is improperly Riemann integrable on its unbounded domain, but it is not absolutely integrable:
formula_178
Indeed, more generally, given any series formula_179 one can consider the associated step function formula_180 defined by formula_181 Then formula_182 converges absolutely, converges conditionally or diverges according to the corresponding behavior of formula_183

The situation is different for the Lebesgue integral, which does not handle bounded and unbounded domains of integration separately (&quot;see below&quot;). The fact that the integral of formula_170 is unbounded in the examples above implies that formula_124 is also not integrable in the Lebesgue sense. In fact, in the Lebesgue theory of integration, given that formula_124 is measurable, formula_124 is (Lebesgue) integrable if and only if formula_170 is (Lebesgue) integrable. However, the hypothesis that formula_124 is measurable is crucial; it is not generally true that absolutely integrable functions on formula_172 are integrable (simply because they may fail to be measurable): let formula_191 be a nonmeasurable subset and consider formula_192 where formula_193 is the characteristic function of formula_194 Then formula_124 is not Lebesgue measurable and thus not integrable, but formula_196 is a constant function and clearly integrable.

On the other hand, a function formula_124 may be Kurzweil-Henstock integrable (gauge integrable) while formula_170 is not. This includes the case of improperly Riemann integrable functions.

In a general sense, on any measure space formula_199 the Lebesgue integral of a real-valued function is defined in terms of its positive and negative parts, so the facts:

# formula_124 integrable implies formula_170 integrable
# formula_124 measurable, formula_170 integrable implies formula_124 integrable

are essentially built into the definition of the Lebesgue integral. In particular, applying the theory to the counting measure on a set formula_205 one recovers the notion of unordered summation of series developed by Moore–Smith using (what are now called) nets. When formula_206 is the set of natural numbers, Lebesgue integrability, unordered summability and absolute convergence all coincide.

Finally, all of the above holds for integrals with values in a Banach space. The definition of a Banach-valued Riemann integral is an evident modification of the usual one. For the Lebesgue integral one needs to circumvent the decomposition into positive and negative parts with Daniell&#x27;s more functional analytic approach, obtaining the Bochner integral.

